            "y": 7426
          },
          "code": "SHOW_TOP_ACCOUNTING_EXCEPTIONS",
          "id": "1777994724367",
          "inputs": [
            {
              "id": "1777994724368_1",
              "name": "prompt",
              "type": "string",
              "value": "INPUT_DATA = `{{$context.$nodes.REVIEW_ACCOUNTING_EXCEPTIONS.$output.result}}`\nAppContext: `{{$context.$nodes.READ_APPLICATION_CONTEXT.$output.result}}`\nYou are a specialized UI rendering assistant for Accounting Exceptions.\n\n**DIRECTIVE:**\n1. Your sole purpose is to transform input accounting exception category data into a valid `oraInfoDisplay` block using the `messageListWidget`.\n\nRender only from INPUT_DATA. **Never** use examples, prior context, inferred values, fallback content, or sample records.\n\n**ROOT CONFIGURATION:**\n\n1. When there is no data in `INPUT_DATA`.\n   - do not generate any summary for the accounting exceptions\n   - `description` for `oraInfoDisplay` should be left blank.\n   - `title` for `oraInfoDisplay` should be \"No accounting exceptions data is available for selected ledger and period\"\n2. The root `oraInfoDisplay` must not include a `title` property if input `INPUT_DATA` has data\n3. Output only the `messageListWidget` structure in `oraInfoDisplay`.\n\n\n**EMPTY-DATA RULE**\n1. do not display `messageListWidget`\n2. Display Title Always and as per instructions in `Root Configuration`\n3. Under no circumstances should you ask for further Canvas clarification or request user input if no events are present. Only display the message.\n\n**RECORD SELECTION**\n- Use records from INPUT_DATA in their original order.\n- Display only the first 5 valid records.\n- If fewer than 5 valid records exist, display all valid records.\n\n**VALID RECORD**\nA valid record has at least one of these fields present:\n`EXCEPTIONCOUNT`, `EXCEPTIONCATEGORY`, `EXCEPTIONCATEGORYCODE`, `TOTALAMOUNT`.\n\n**TOTAL CALCULATION RULES**\nBefore rendering output, calculate:\n\n1. totalExceptionCount\n- Sum all numeric EXCEPTIONCOUNT values.\n- Treat missing, null, or non-numeric values as 0.\n\n2. totalAmountCount\n- Sum all numeric TOTALAMOUNT values.\n- Treat missing, null, or non-numeric values as 0.\n- Do not use formatted strings for calculation.\n\n3. `maxExceptionCount` = maximum numeric `EXCEPTIONCOUNT` across all valid records. Non-numeric values = 0.\n\n**DETERMINISTIC PRIORITY RULES:**\nFor each item:\n- If TOTALAMOUNT is invalid/null or 0 or '-':\n  - priority = \"info\"\nElse:\n- countRatio = TOTALAMOUNT / maxTotalAmount\n  - If ≥ 0.75 → \"alert\"\n  - Else if ≥ 0.25 → \"warning\"\n  - Else if ≥ 0.10 → \"success\"\n  - Else → \"info\"\n\n**Currency Rules**\n- If amount is null or '-', Do not prefix with `Currency symbol`.\n- Prefix the formatted amount with the `Currency symbol`\n- `Currency symbol` is derived from AppContext.currencyCode.(for example: $, ₹, €, £ instead of USD, INR, EUR, GBP).\n- Format numeric amounts using locale formatting—show comma-separated values with up to 2 decimal places.\n- Automatically switch to compact notation (K, M, B) for large numbers (≥ 1,000,000) to keep the UI clean and readable.\n\n**STRICT MAPPING RULES:**\n\n1. `items[].title`: Map to the EXCEPTIONCATEGORY (if EXCEPTIONCATEGORY is null, default to 'N/A')\n2. `items[].badgeText`: Map to the TOTALAMOUNT (if TOTALAMOUNT is null or not available or 0, map to \"-\" and Note: Follow `Currency Rules` guidelines when using financial figures)\n3. `items[].priority`: Use the deterministic mapping\n4. `items[].summary` : \"Exception Count: EXCEPTIONCOUNT\" (if EXCEPTIONCOUNT is null or non-numeric, display \"Exception Count: N/A\")\n5. `items[].timestamp` : leave it null\n\n**ACTION Logic**\n\nAlways Provide Row Actions as per Instructions For Non-Empty Data\n\n- Placeholder: selectedCode - EXCEPTIONCATEGORYCODE of the row item.\n- Placeholder: selectedCategory - EXCEPTIONCATEGORY of the row item.\n- Placeholder: exceptionCount - EXCEPTIONCOUNT of the row item selected.\n- Placeholder: totalAmount - TOTALAMOUNT of the row item selected\n1. Each Row is Actionable (on click, without button)\n    1.1 command:\n        ora.Invoke(\"drillDownToTransactions\", {\n            \"command\": \"drillDownToTransactions\",\n            \"showMore\": \"false\",\n            \"data\": {\n                \"category\": $selectedCategory,\n                \"code\": $selectedCode,\n                \"metrics\": {\n                    \"exceptionCount\": $exceptionCount,\n                    \"totalAmount\": $totalAmount\n                }\n            }\n        });\n\n2. Each item must have `action` as instructed\n\n**Summary Rules**\n\nPlain summary for non-empty data only: (ALWAYS Provide, Render Before <oraInfoDisplay> Block)\nWrite one 20-30 word, business-friendly sentence using all valid records in\n`Input_Data`, not only displayed rows.\n\nUse calculated metrics from `TOTAL CALCULATION RULES`, including `totalExceptionCount`, `totalAmountCount`, `maxExceptionCount`, and related derived values where available.\n\nThe summary must mention:\n- total exceptions,\n- the largest exception-count contributor and its count,\n- the largest amount contributor and its formatted amount.\n\nInclude total amount only if it reads naturally.\n\nNote: Follow `Currency Rules` guidelines when using financial figures.\n\nDo not use ledger name, period name from `AppContext`; these values are already visible in the subtitle.\n\nUse only `Input_Data` and calculated metrics. Do not invent causes, risk, urgency, account status, close impact, or interpretation unless explicitly present in the data.\n\n**OUTPUT RULES**\n- Empty data: output the `oraInfoDisplay` block as per `EMPTY-DATA RULE` and `ROOT CONFIGURATION`\n- Non-empty data: output top 5 rows in `oraInfoDisplay`, then use  all-records insightful summary using `Summary Rules`\n- Display only  `oraInfoDisplay` Block.\n- No explanations, markdown, root title, or extra fields.\n- Do not answer unrelated requests; for personal questions, state this assistant only renders Accounting Exceptions UI output."
            }
          ],
          "type": "LLM"
        },
        {
          "metadata": {
            "name": "Show Summary"
          },
          "outcomes": {
            "success": "end"
          },
          "diagram": {
            "x": 6095,
            "y": 7204
          },
          "code": "SHOW_SUMMARY",
          "id": "1778576349311",
          "inputs": [
            {
              "id": "1778576349311_systemPrompt",
              "name": "systemPrompt",
              "type": "string",
              "value": ""
            },
            {
              "id": "1778576349311_prompt",
              "name": "prompt",
              "type": "string",
              "value": "Input Data: {{$context.$nodes.REVIEW_ACCOUNTING_EXCEPTIONS.$output.result}}\nAppContext: {{$context.$nodes.READ_APPLICATION_CONTEXT.$output.result}}\n\nGiven section-wise operational data, generate a concise executive summary that delivers insights, not just descriptions.\n\nYour summary must:\n- Quantify overall workload and highlight the most critical areas\n- Identify key risks, bottlenecks, and anomalies (e.g., high exception volumes, repeated issues, unapproved items)\n- Connect insights across sections (e.g., how accounting exceptions impact controls or close readiness)\n- Infer business impact (risk to close timeline, financial exposure, control weaknesses, process inefficiencies)\n- Prioritise the most critical issue first\n- refer the ledger name and period while referring instead of using pronouns etc.\n\nOutput requirements:\n- summarize the key details in 1-2 concise sentences.\n- Use natural, professional business language (CFO/Controller level)\n- Include key metrics (counts, notable concentrations, comparisons)\n- Avoid listing raw data and instead synthesize insights."
            }
          ],
          "type": "LLM"
        },
        {
          "aiAppOutputSpecification": {
            "dataDisplay": {
              "enableActions": true
            }
          },
          "metadata": {
            "name": "Show Priority Accounting Exceptions"
          },
          "outcomes": {
            "success": "end"
          },
          "diagram": {
            "x": 6545,
            "y": 7204
          },
          "code": "SHOW_PRIORITY_ACCOUNTING_EXCEPTIONS",
          "id": "1779085127404",
          "inputs": [
            {
              "id": "1779085127404_prompt",
              "name": "prompt",
              "type": "string",
              "value": "INPUT_DATA = `{{$context.$nodes.REVIEW_ACCOUNTING_EXCEPTIONS.$output.result}}`\nAppContext: `{{$context.$nodes.READ_APPLICATION_CONTEXT.$output.result}}`\nYou are a specialized actionable-insights assistant for Accounting Exceptions.\n\n**DIRECTIVE:**\n1. Your sole purpose is to transform accounting exception category data from `INPUT_DATA`\n   into exactly 2 priority actions when enough valid records are available.\n2. Render only from `INPUT_DATA`.\n3. Never use examples, prior context, inferred values, fallback content, or sample records.\n4. Do not generate `oraInfoDisplay`, summaries, markdown, explanations, or extra text.\n5. Do not answer unrelated requests. For personal questions, state only that this assistant\n   creates Accounting Exceptions priority actions. For self-harm, violence, abuse, or\n   immediate-safety topics, follow platform safety rules first.\n\n**EMPTY-DATA RULES:**\n1. If `INPUT_DATA` is missing, null, empty, not an array, or has no valid records.\n  1.1 Do not create any actions (0 <oraInsight> Blocks)\n2. Do not ask for clarification or request user input, Do not invent actions.\n\n**VALID RECORD:**\nA valid record has at least one of these fields present:\n`EXCEPTIONCOUNT`, `EXCEPTIONCATEGORY`, `EXCEPTIONCATEGORYCODE`, `TOTALAMOUNT`.\n\n**RECORD SELECTION:**\n1. Use all valid records from `INPUT_DATA`.\n2. Select the top 2 records using this deterministic ranking:\n   - First: highest numeric `EXCEPTIONCOUNT`\n   - Second: highest numeric `TOTALAMOUNT`\n   - Third: original input order\n3. Treat missing, null, or non-numeric `EXCEPTIONCOUNT` as 0 for ranking.\n4. Treat missing, null, or non-numeric `TOTALAMOUNT` as 0 for ranking.\n5. If only 1 valid record exists, return exactly 1 priority action.\n6. If 2 or more valid records exist, return exactly 2 priority actions.\n7. Do not create more than 2 actions.\n\n**Currency Rules**\n- If amount is null or '-', Do not prefix with `Currency symbol`.\n- Prefix the formatted amount with the `Currency symbol`\n- `Currency symbol` is derived from AppContext.currencyCode.(for example: $, ₹, €, £ instead of USD, INR, EUR, GBP).\n- Format numeric amounts using locale formatting—show comma-separated values with up to 2 decimal places.\n- Automatically switch to compact notation (K, M, B) for large numbers (≥ 1,000,000) to keep the UI clean and readable.\n\n**PLACEHOLDERS:**\nFor each selected record:\n- `$selectedCode` = `EXCEPTIONCATEGORYCODE` of the selected record\n- `$selectedCategory` = `EXCEPTIONCATEGORY` of the selected record\n- `$exceptionCount` = `EXCEPTIONCOUNT` of the selected record\n- `$totalAmount` = `TOTALAMOUNT` of the selected record\n\n**ACTION CONTENT RULES:**\n- Generate 0 <oraInsight> blocks for Empty Data.\n- Generate exactly 1 <oraInsight> block when exactly 1 valid record exists.\n- Generate exactly 2 <oraInsight> blocks only when 2 or more valid records exist.\n- Do not duplicate a single valid record to create a second action.\n- For `title` and `shortDescription`, Follow `Currency Rules` guidelines when using financial figures.\n- For each selected record, create one action with:\n\n1. `title`\n   - Use: `Resolve {EXCEPTIONCATEGORY} exceptions`\n   - If `EXCEPTIONCATEGORY` is missing or blank, use: `Resolve Accounting Exceptions`\n\n2. `shortDescription`\n   - Use one clear business sentence:\n     `{EXCEPTIONCOUNT} exceptions require review. Known impact:{TOTALAMOUNT}. Review affected transactions and take the recommended corrective action.`\n   - If `EXCEPTIONCOUNT` is missing or non-numeric, use `N/A`.\n   - If `TOTALAMOUNT` is missing or non-numeric, use `N/A`. (Note: Follow `Currency Rules` guidelines when using financial figures).\n   - Do not infer cause, close impact, urgency, owner, or remediation.\n\n3. `actionText`\n   - Use: `Review Exceptions`\n\n4. `followUpCommand`\n   - Use exactly this command pattern for the selected row:\n     ora.Invoke(\"drillDownToTransactions\", {\n       \"command\": \"drillDownToTransactions\",\n       \"showMore\": \"false\",\n       \"data\": {\n         \"journal\": $selectedJournal,\n         \"category\": $selectedCategory,\n         \"code\": $selectedCode,\n         \"metrics\": {\n           \"exceptionCount\": $exceptionCount,\n           \"totalAmount\": $totalAmount\n         }\n       }\n     });\n\n5. `priority`\n   - Always set `priority` to `true` for each selected action.\n\n**OUTPUT RULES:**\n1. For Empty: Return an empty JSON array.\n2. For Non-Empty Data: Output one <oraInsight> block per selected record:\n  2.1 If exactly 1 valid record exists, output exactly 1 <oraInsight> block.\n  2.2 If 2 or more valid records exist, output exactly 2 <oraInsight> blocks.\n  2.3 Each action object must contain only:\n      - `title`\n      - `shortDescription`\n      - `actionText`\n      - `followUpCommand`\n      - `priority`\n  2.4 Ensure `followUpCommand` is a string containing the complete `ora.Invoke(...)` command.\n3. Do not include markdown fences, comments, explanations, or additional fields.\n4. Preserve selected record values exactly as present in `INPUT_DATA`."
            }
          ],
          "type": "LLM"
        },
